body:
Dug into this and found the exact edge case where it happens, related to a `return` in the block. Managed to create a minimal reproduction based on the package code:

```js
// app/assert.js
export function assert(a, b) {
  if (a !== b) {
    throw new Error(`Assertion failed: ${a} !== ${b}`);
  }
}

```

```js
// app/page.js
import { assert } from "./assert";

function runGetClassesOrUseCache() {
  use_cache: {
    assert(1, 1);
    if (true) {
      break use_cache;
    }
    return "value a";
  }
  {
    assert(2, 2);
  }

  assert(3, 3);

  return "value b";
}

export default function Page() {
  return <h1>{runGetClassesOrUseCache()}</h1>;
}
```

When removing `return "value a"` it works correctly.

This is related to how imports / exports get mangled names and those need to be replaced in the code, it's catching the first `use_cache: {` case but then fails to replace the second case. We'll get this fixed.

